To update an object property in JavaScript, you can use either dot notation or bracket notation.

Using dot notation:

```javascript
var obj = {name: "John", age: 30};
obj.name = "Jane";
obj.age = 35;
```

Using bracket notation:

```javascript
var obj = {name: "John", age: 30};
obj["name"] = "Jane";
obj["age"] = 35;
```

You can also use a variable inside the bracket notation to update dynamic object properties:

```javascript
var obj = {name: "John", age: 30};
var propName = "name";
obj[propName] = "Jane";
```

Sure! Here is an example of how to update an object in JavaScript while following best practices:

```javascript
// Define the object
const person = {
  name: "John",
  age: 30,
  city: "New York",
};

// Define a function to update the object properties
function updatePerson(name, age, city) {
  if (name) { // If name parameter is provided
    person.name = name;
  }
  if (age) { // If age parameter is provided
    person.age = age;
  }
  if (city) { // If city parameter is provided
    person.city = city;
  }
}

// Call the function to update the object properties
updatePerson("Jane", null, "San Francisco");

// Check if the object properties are updated
console.log(person); // {name: "Jane", age: 30, city: "San Francisco"}
```

In this example, we follow the following best practices:
- We declare the object using `const` to prevent accidental reassignment and promote immutability.
- We define a function to update the object properties, which makes our code more modular and easier to maintain.
- We use conditional statements to check whether the parameters are provided or not, which prevents the accidental overwrite of the properties with `undefined` or `null` values.
- We pass `null` for the parameters that we don't want to update, instead of omitting them altogether. This makes our code more explicit and easier to understand.

